1. LLM agent graph (Claude mocking) — Your code asks Claude "is this trade good?" To test it, we'd make a fake Claude
  that returns a canned reply like "yes, conviction 80." Problem: if we tweak the prompt later, the real Claude might
  reply differently, but our fake doesn't change — so the test still passes while production breaks. The test gives
  false confidence.

  2. Full DB integration / fixture infrastructure — Most code talks to your Postgres database. To test it without
  polluting your real data, we'd need to spin up a temporary throwaway database for every test, load the schema, run the
   test, delete it. A "fixture" is just code that sets up that throwaway state. Building this is fiddly (Docker,
  pg_dump, pytest plugins) — half a day of work that doesn't actually catch bugs you'd ship to production.

  3. HTTP clients / recorded responses — When data/marketdata.py calls MarketData's API, the API returns JSON. To test
  "does our code parse that JSON right?" without hitting their server every test run (slow + rate-limited + costs
  credits), we record one real response to a file, then "replay" that file in tests as if it came from the network.
  Tools called vcrpy or respx do this. Useful but not critical.

  4. Sweeper end-to-end with real options source — You're right, once MarketData is wired the sweeper will just work
  with real chains. This isn't really a test gap, it's an operational milestone: subscribe → wire → run → see results. I
   overstated it as a "gap."